York Ave., at the N.E. corner of East 89th Street. Also shown is East 89th Street, north side, east from and including York Ave., to the East River. Buildings shown form a portion of the House of the Good Shepherd.

January 31, 1928.

P. L. Sperr.

(1)
York Avenue (Avenue A), east side, from 89th to 91st Streets, showing, on the northeast corner of 89th Street, one of the buildings of the House of the Good Shepherd, "a house of refuge for fallen women and girls, who desire to reform" (King's Handbook of New York City, 1892). Other buildings of the House of the Good Shepherd are farther east in the same block.

The House of the Good Shepherd was founded in 1857; this building on the N.E. corner of 89th Street, which used to belong to St. Ann's Home, was built around 1885.
St. Ann's Home for Destitute Children, founded in 1879, occupies the S.E. corner of 90th Street. The whole block, at the time of this picture, is about to be razed. In the block from 91st to 92nd Streets may be seen the new garage of the Municipal Asphalt Plant.

January 31, 1928.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
The same, six years later, showing the playground on the site of the demolished buildings from 89th to 90th Streets.
October 9, 1934.

P. L. Sperr.

89th Street, north side, east from and including York Avenue.
March 29, 1929.
P. L. Sperr.

York Avenue, west side, from 89th to 91st Streets, with clearing on east side from 89th to 90th Streets.
The block from 89th to 90th Streets was occupied till about 1918 by St. Joseph's Orphan Asylum, an institution for German Children, incorporated in 1859. The cigar factory on the S.W. corner of 90th Street used to be one of the Orphan Asylum buildings, erected in the early 1880's.
1731-33-35 York Avenue (formerly Avenue A), at and adjoining the N.W. corner of 90th Street, antedate 1891; 1791 on the corner is a frame house. The 5-story buildings, above them, to the corner of 91st Street, were not built till around 1895.
March 29, 1929.
P. L. Sperr.
